✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Nice clash. The statement is easy to understand and, as far as I was able to try, the 4 testpairs deal well with the order / multiple names.

A lot of good clashers in that first test too. Sad to see that the main culprit ended in the validator :D

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: This puzzle has a simple solution by hand, but the part here is figuring out how to program it.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: I like this one! It requires a couple of steps (rather than a quick single line of code), which are doable in 5 minutes but not too easy.

Hi @masterpoo :-) !
I agree with your Contribution.
=> I upvote for you.

My custom Python Solution :
l=sorted([[f:=input(),sorted(f.lower(),reverse=True)[0]] for i in range(int(input()))],key=lambda x:x[1])
a=l[0][1]
#print(*l, a, file=sys.stderr, flush=True)
l=[*filter(lambda x:x[1]==a,l)]
#print(*l, file=sys.stderr, flush=True)
print(*sorted([n[0] for n in l]))

Good clash!
I think there should be an edge case where the last name of the list is in the result, so that we aren't allowed to ignore the last update of a result constructed in a loop.
Also it should be specified that the names are considered case insensitive for the sake of comparison but case sensitive when they need to be output.

Very minor caveats:

- No space before "?" in "first name first ?"
- Output - The first names that would be learn first, -> that would be learnt / learned
- "separated by spaces" in the statement but "separated by space" in the output

Personally I would rename first name to name, so it's a bit easier to not mix bits like this one on the first read:
- "Given a list of first names, who will be able to write their first name first ?"
- "The first names that would be learn first"

Plus you already did it in the clash title, so there's that.

Fun clash.

Your contribution has been uploaded twice. Please remove one of them. The other link is:
https://www.codingame.com/contribute/view/82515c1f477783e69acdd2f27c1314af33e49

Thanks.

Constraints / Stub generator
* Please change "firstname" to "name" for consistency.

Thanks.
I edited the text to clarify. The case sensitivity to output is not important as every name start with an upper letter followed by lower letters. I also modified the 4th test to output the last name.
